Databases w/ R

library(DBI)
library(odbc)

con <- dbConnect(odbc(), 
                      Driver = "SQL Server", 
                      Server = "localhost\\SQLEXPRESS", 
                      Database = "master", 
                      Trusted_Connection = "True")
dbGetQuery(con, "Select Top 10 * From flights")
Select top 10 * from "flights"

dplyr & dbplyr

Install dbplyr, along with dplyr, to use interact with databases

devtools::install_github("tidyverse/dbplyr")
library(dplyr)

Attaching package: dplyr

The following objects are masked from package:stats:

    filter, lag

The following objects are masked from package:base:

    intersect, setdiff, setequal, union
library(dbplyr)

Attaching package: dbplyr

The following objects are masked from package:dplyr:

    ident, sql
flights <- tbl(con, "flights")
object.size(flights)
7584 bytes
flights
NA
flights %>%
  tally()
flights %>%
  group_by(month) %>%
  tally()

show_query()

flights %>%
  group_by(name) %>%
  tally() %>%
  show_query()
<SQL>
SELECT "name", COUNT(*) AS "n"
FROM "flights"
GROUP BY "name"

join tables

airports <- tbl(con, "airports")

new_flights <- flights %>%
  left_join(airports, by = c("dest" = "faa"))

new_flights

collect()

by_location <- new_flights %>%
  group_by(name, lon, lat) %>%
  tally() %>%
  collect()

by_location

plotting

library(ggplot2) 

by_location %>%
  ggplot() +
  geom_point(aes(x = lon, y= lat, size = n, color = n), alpha = 0.5)

Direct insights

new_flights %>%
  group_by(name) %>%
  tally() %>%
  arrange(desc(n)) %>%  # desc() inside arrange() get the top counts
  head(10)
NA

pull() command

top_names <- new_flights %>%
  group_by(name) %>%
  tally() %>%
  arrange(desc(n)) %>%
  head(10) %>% 
  collect() %>%
  pull("name")

top_names
 [1] "Chicago Ohare Intl"                 "Hartsfield Jackson Atlanta Intl"    "Los Angeles Intl"                  
 [4] "General Edward Lawrence Logan Intl" "Orlando Intl"                       "Charlotte Douglas Intl"            
 [7] "San Francisco Intl"                 "Fort Lauderdale Hollywood Intl"     "Miami Intl"                        
[10] "Ronald Reagan Washington Natl"

Take advantage of dplyrs laziness

top_flights <- new_flights %>%
  filter(name %in% top_names)

Use View() to preview some of the data in the familiar data viewer

top_flights %>%
  head(1000) %>%
  collect() %>%
  View("top_flights")

Easily transition from data manipulation to plotting, without needing to import the data

top_flights %>%
  group_by(Month) %>%
  tally() %>%
  collect() %>%
  ggplot() +
    geom_area(aes(x = Month , y = n), fill = "blue", alpha = 0.5)

NA

Thanks to the tidyverse approach, an entirly new plot can be built by adding one single line, and the data is still summarized inside the database

top_flights %>%
  filter(distance > 2000) %>%  # Added 
  group_by(Month) %>%
  tally() %>%
  collect() %>%
  ggplot() +
    geom_area(aes(x = Month , y = n), fill = "blue", alpha = 0.5)

NA

Temporary tables

temp_flights <- new_flights %>%
  group_by(name) %>%
  tally() 
temp_flights <- copy_to(con, temp_flights, "temp_flights")

  arrange(desc(n))
